<p></p>.<p>
Warmth of a joint occurs in many normal and abnormal settings. Joint warmth can be a result of a warm covering over a joint and be normal. Joint warmth is a normal part of the healing process after surgical replacement of joints (arthroplasty). Injury, including <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/broken_bone_types_of_bone_fractures/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">fracture</a>, <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/bruises/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">bruising</a>, and bleeding into a joint, can lead to joint warmth. Joint warmth can also be a result of diseases of, or injury to, the joint that cause inflammation. These diseases and injuries include <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/arthritis/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">arthritis</a>, such as <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/rheumatoid_arthritis/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">rheumatoid arthritis</a> and <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/psoriatic_arthritis/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">psoriatic arthritis</a>, as well as infection directly or indirectly involving the joint, such as from bacteria or <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/viral_infections_pictures_slideshow/article.htm" rel="slide" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">viruses</a> and <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/septic_arthritis/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">septic arthritis</a>, <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/osgood-schlatter_disease/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">Osgood-Schlatter disease</a>, repetitive motion injuries, <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/cellulitis/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">cellulitis</a>, slipped capital femoral epiphysis, <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/broken_bone_types_of_bone_fractures/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">stress fracture</a>, dislocated knee, <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/sickle_cell/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">sickle cell disease</a>, <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/sporotrichosis/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">sporotrichosis</a>, <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/skin_problems_pictures_slideshow/article.htm" rel="slide" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">abscess</a>, <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/obesity_weight_loss/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">obesity</a>, osteochondritis desiccans, knee strain, <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/rheumatic_fever/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">rheumatic fever</a>, <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/torn_meniscus/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">torn meniscus</a>, ACL injury, and patellofemoral <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/pain_management/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">pain</a> syndrome.
</p>.<p class="credits">REFERENCE:<br><br>

Firestein, Gary S., et al. <i>Kelley's Textbook of Rheumatology, 9th Edition</i>. Philadelphia, PA: Saunders, 2013</p>